t the controversial and high-profile nature of naval architecture. The technological transformation of the Navy dominated the British government and engineering communities. This book explores its history, revealing how ship design became a modern science, the ways that actors competed for authority within the British state and why the nature of naval power changed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aNaval art and sciencexHistoryx19th centuryxHistory. 0aNaval art and sciencexHistoryy19th century. 0aWarships - History - 19th century. 0aWarshipsxHistoryx19th century. 0aWarshipsxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Military / Naval.2bisacsh  a1830 Whig government.  aCaptain.  aPax Britannica.  aRoyal Navy.  aRoyal Sovereign.  aWarrior.  anaval architecture.  anaval thinking.  asailor-designer identity.  aship design.  asteam powered machine.  awooden walls.1 aLeggett, Don, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2015 eBook-Packagez978311128311140uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611187640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526111876423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526111876/original  a978-3-11-128311-1  Manchester University Press 2015 eBook-Packageb2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles